  "prompt": "If space (the universe) is a sphere or saddle shape, then what is outside of that? What do you call the empty space outside that comes after?",
  "response": "This is a complex question in cosmology and physics. The truth is, we don't know for certain what, if anything, exists \"outside\" the universe. There are several theoretical perspectives:\n\n1. Some physicists argue that the concept of \"outside\" may not be meaningful, as space and time themselves might be properties of the universe, not something contained within it.\n\n2. In some models, the universe might be:\n- Finite but unbounded (like the surface of a sphere, where there's no \"edge\")\n- Infinite\n- Part of a multiverse\n- Potentially existing within a larger dimensional space\n\n3. Current scientific understanding suggests that asking what's \"outside\" the universe might be like asking what's \"north\" of the North Pole - the question itself might not make logical sense within our current understanding of physics.\n\n4. Theoretical models like string theory and quantum physics propose complex scenarios about potential \"spaces\" beyond our observable universe, but these remain highly speculative.\n\nThe short answer is: We don't know definitively what, if anything, exists \"outside\" the universe. The question remains an open mystery in cosmology and theoretical physics.\n\nScientists continue to research and develop models to understand the nature and potential boundaries of our universe.",
